{ @@HeaderStart@@Philipp Schlosser - Loek Van Wely, Belfort 2012@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  In this example Black achieves the ...c6-c5 break, and later obtains unpleasant pressure against White's d-pawn, which eventually decides the game. } 1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. b3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. d4 Rc8 11. e4 { An alternative is  11.Rac1  waiting for Black to take decisive action in the centre. After  11...c5  12.dxc5  bxc5  13.Rfd1  Qe7  14.g3  Rfd8  15.cxd5  exd5  16.Nh4  Bb8  we reach a hanging pawns structure with mutual chances, as in Ivanchuk - Aronian, Linares 2009. } 11... Nxe4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4 { We have reached the key structure, but Black's opening play has been very solid and he is ready to dispute White's control of the centre with: } 13... Nf6 14. Qh4 c5 { Once again a well-timed ...c6-c5 break allows Black to release his position, equalizing the game. } 15. Rad1 { Threatening dxc5 followed by Bxf6 creating some weaknesses in Black's camp.   If  15.dxc5  Rxc5   15...Bxc5 !?  16.Rad1  Ne4 !  Black manages to fully equalize the game. } 15... Ne4 16. Qxd8 { After this natural exchange White begins to struggle to maintain the balance; maybe he thought this would be enough for a draw? Let's see what happens.   An alternative is  16.Qh5  cxd4  17.Bxd4  Qe7  18.Bd3  f5  when Black is comfortable, as in the game Caruana - Gustafsson, Rogoska Slatina 2009.   The strange-looking  16.d5  does not give Black problems after:  16...Qxh4  17.Nxh4  Be7  18.Nf3   if  18.Bf3  Black has many good options, such as  18...Nxf2 !?  19.Kxf2  Bxh4+  20.g3  Bg5  with level chances  18...exd5  19.cxd5  Rcd8  The d5-pawn is both a weakness and a strength, this the position is approximately level.   The option  16.Qh3 !?  should be considered. } 16... Rfxd8 { It is now White who faces problems due to the central pressure. } 17. Nd2 { Aiming to further simplify the position, but this is a fresh inaccuracy which only increases White's difficulties.   Instead  17.dxc5 ?!  would not solve White's problems either:  17...Bxc5  18.Ne5  Black has many promising options at his disposal, for example:  18...Nxf2 !?  19.Rxf2  Rxd1+  20.Bxd1  Rd8  21.Be2  Bxf2+  22.Kxf2  Bxg2 !  =+ The bishop is immune, since  23.Kxg2 ?  loses to  23...Rd2   It is preferable to play  17.Bd3  cxd4  18.Nxd4  Bb4  19.Nc2  Be7  after which Black's lead is very small. } 17... Nxd2 18. Rxd2 Be5 { A nice move, pressuring White's main weakness, the d4-pawn.   If instead  18...Bf4 ?!  White simply replies  19.Rdd1  followed by  dxc5  solving all his problems. } 19. Rfd1 Bf4 { Well done! The two-step move ...Be5-f4 puts White in an awkward position since the d1-square is no longer free to allow Rd2-d1. } 20. Rc2 { Even worse is  20.Rd3  Be4  21.Rh3  Bf5  22.Rf3  Bg5  =+ when the rook is awkwardly placed on  f3  and White is still under pressure. } 20... Be4 21. Bd3 Bxd3 22. Rxd3 Rd7 { Preparing to double rooks on the d-file, while White cannot release the pressure on d4.   The tempting  22...cxd4 !?  does not work as well after:  23.Rxd4   23.Bxd4 ?  loses to  23...e5  23...Rxd4  24.Bxd4  Rd8  Now White must give up a pawn.  25.g3   25.Be3 ??  Rd1#  25...Bxg3   Or  25...Rxd4  26.gxf4  Rxf4  27.Rd2  with level chances  26.Bxb6  Bxh2+  27.Kxh2  axb6  The endgame arising is quite unclear and after  28.c5  bxc5  29.Rxc5  it seems that White's two pawns on the queenside are more than enough to fight against Black's kingside pawns. } 23. g3 { Similar is  23.Re2  Rcd8  24.g3  Bg5  25.d5  exd5  26.cxd5  Kf8  with good winning chances for Black due to the weak d5-pawn. } 23... Be5 24. d5 Bxb2 25. Rxb2 exd5 26. cxd5 Kf8 { We have reached an interesting rook endgame, which is somewhat typical of this pawn structure  (once Black has released his position with ...c6-c5)  ; therefore I will analyze a few variations to help explain Black's path to victory. } 27. Rbd2 Re8 28. Kg2 Ke7 29. Re3+ { The best practical chance is probably  29.d6+  Kd8  30.Rd5  Re6  and the d6-pawn becomes vulnerable as Black intends to follow up with  ...Kc8-b7-c6  capturing it.  31.a3  Attempting to play b3-b4 to open the c-file and make the king manoeuvre difficult, is met by:  31...a5 !  =+ Winning this endgame with Black will not be simple, but at least White cannot easily secure a draw either. } 29... Kd8 30. Kf3 Rde7 31. h4 { Transferring to a pawn endgame with  31.Rxe7 ?!  Rxe7  ∓  32.Re2 ?  loses after  32...Rxe2 !  33.Kxe2  Kd7  34.Kd3  Kd6  35.Kc4  a6  36.a4  h5  when White falls into zugzwang after  37.f4  g6  38.h3  f6  39.g4  h4  40.f5  g5   Of course  31.d6 ?  loses a pawn immediately after  31...Rxe3+  32.fxe3  Kd7  followed by  ...Re6xd6. } 31... Kd7 32. Kf4 Kd6 { Black's play has been so precise over the last few moves that I cannot find good suggestions for White to stay in the game. Black's king on d6 is ideal and White's defensive task becomes extremely difficult. } 33. g4 b5 34. g5 { After  34.a4 !?  Black has many ways to improve his position. I suggest  34...b4 !  with the potential threat  ...c5-c4  to create a strong passed pawn on  b4. } 34... Re5 35. h5 { The alternative  35.Rde2  Rxe3  36.fxe3  Kxd5  37.e4+  Ke6  ∓ is not satisfactory for White either. } 35... g6 36. h6 { White has achieved a threatening pawn on h6, though accurate play from Black will prevent the h7-pawn from being captured. } 36... Rf5+ 37. Kg4 Ree5 38. Rxe5 Rxe5 39. f4 Rxd5 40. Rc2 Rd3 41. Re2 c4 { Black will now push his extra pawn and win easily as White lacks effective counterplay. } 42. bxc4 bxc4 43. Re8 { 43.Rc2  doesn't help. Black plays  43...c3  followed by  ...Kd5-d4  and  ...Rd2. } 43... Rd5 { Threatening ...c4-c3-c2 together with ...Rc5.   But not  43...c3 ??  44.Rd8+  Kc5  45.Rxd3  +- } 44. Kf3 { If  44.Rd8+  Kc5  45.Rh8  Rd7 !  46.Kf3   The optimistic  46.Rxh7 ??  runs into  46...f5+ !  47.gxf6  Rxh7  -+  46...c3  47.Rc8+  Kb4  White's lack of counterplay makes Black's winning task relatively simple, for example  48.Ke3  a5  49.Rc6  a4  50.Rc8  Ka3  51.Rxc3+  Kxa2  and the rest is simple. } 44... c3 45. Rd8+ { Or  45.Ke3  c2  46.Rc8  Rc5  47.Rxc5  Kxc5  48.Kd2  Kd4  49.Kxc2  Ke4  and wins. } 45... Kc5 46. Rc8+ Kd4 47. Rc7 Kd3 48. Rxf7 c2 49. Rc7 Kd2 50. Ke4 Rd8 { Final remarks  1. White lost almost without making a mistake. His biggest problem was in the opening, as when he played e3-e4 he knew he could not prevent ...c6-c5 which allowed Black to equalize easily.   2. Later, White's mistake was simplifying the position unfavourably with 16.Qxd8 and 17.Nd2. It seems like White assumed the position would be just equal, but he missed the pressure his d-pawn would face. Then Van Wely imposed his positional advantage with great precision. } *

