{ @@HeaderStart@@Vadim Zvjaginsev - Alexander Evdokimov, 64th Russian Championship, Taganrog 2011@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This is an example of how Black may carry out the ...b7-b5 break, and how White can meet this break and turn the c6-pawn into a weakness. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nf3 Nd7 7. Bd3 e6 8. O-O Ngf6 9. b3 Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. c4 { White enjoys a small advantage as is usual in this type of structure. } 11... Qa5 12. a3 { Preventing 12...Ba3.   If  12.Re1  Black can trade bishops with  12...Ba3  thus decreasing his space problem. } 12... Rfd8 13. Re1 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 b5 { The ...b7-b5 break is quite typical for this structure and it often gives Black decent counterplay. } 15. Nf5 { White cannot afford to be careless in this position, for example  15.cxb5 ?!  Qxb5  16.Qc2   After  16.Qxb5  cxb5  we reach an isolated queen pawn position, which in this case is favourable for Black due to the lack of attacking prospects for White  16...c5  and Black has a very comfortable position.   If  15.b4 ?!  bxc4  16.Qxc4  Qb5  17.Rec1  a5  it is White who must play for equality, as the queenside pawns will be traded and he will be left with a weak isolated queen pawn.   Waiting with  15.Re2 ?!  does not work well either since  15...bxc4  16.bxc4   16.Qxc4  Qb5  and Black is okay here too  16...Rab8  =+ gives Black good chances to exert pressure along the b-file. Note how weak the pawns on  a3  and  c4  have become. } 15... Bf8 { 15...exf5  16.Rxe7  bxc4  17.Qxc4   If  17.bxc4  Ne4  White's rook is awkwardly placed on  e7.  17...Nd5  18.Re2  Rab8  and the position is rather unclear since White has a better structure, but his bishop on  b2  is quite useless at the moment. } 16. Ne3 { After a very nice rearrangement, White is now ready to effectively meet the capture ...bxc4 with Nxc4. } 16... Rab8 17. Qc2 bxc4 { Preferable is  17...Qc7 !?  keeping the tension on the queenside:  18.Rec1  a5  and if  19.cxb5 ?!   19.Bc3 !?  +=  19...Rxb5  Black is okay. } 18. Nxc4 Qb5 19. b4 { The importance of White's manoeuvre Ng3-f5-e3-c4 lies in the fact that Black is now unable to eliminate his queenside weaknesses with ...a7-a5. For this reason, White enjoys a lasting positional advantage. } 19... h6 20. Bc1 Nd5 21. Bd2 { White improves his bishop, which was previously useless on b2. } 21... Rbc8 22. Rac1 Qa6 23. h3 Rc7 24. Na5 Bd6 25. Qc4 { Trading queens makes the weakness on c6 more accessible to White's pieces. } 25... Qxc4 26. Rxc4 Rdc8 27. Rec1 Ne7 { It is clear how White dominates the game, but it is not quite so easy to find a winning plan as Black's position remains solid. } 28. R4c2 Nb6 29. Ne5 { A good decision: Black is forced to give up his dark-squared bishop after which White not only gets rid of his isolated queen's pawn, but also gains good control of the dark squares.   If White first decides to improve his king with  29.Kf1  then Black has the option to play  29...f6 !?  depriving White of the e5-square. } 29... Bxe5 30. dxe5 Nbd5 31. Kf1 Kf8 32. Rc5 Ke8 33. Nc4 Kd7 34. Ra5 { Somewhat inaccurate.   It is preferable to first centralize the king:  34.Ke2  Nf5  35.Kd3  Rd8  36.Ke4  and now White has many plans to improve, for example  36...Rdc8  37.g4  Nfe7  38.Be3 !?  (to be followed by Ra5)  38...Nxe3  39.fxe3  Nd5  40.Kf3  ± followed by e3-e4,  Rd1  or  Nd6  when Black is in serious trouble. } 34... Nf5 35. Be3 { Another inaccuracy.   Now it is too late for  35.Ke2 ?  due to  35...Nd4+  36.Kd3  Nb3  winning an exchange.   White can preserve his advantage with:  35.Rc5 !?  += } 35... Nfxe3+ 36. fxe3 f6 { Black returns the favour.   He missed  36...c5 !  37.b5  Rb8  38.Ke2  Nb6  when the position is close to equal. } 37. e4 { 37.Ke2 !?  was also strong. } 37... Nb6 38. Rxa7 { This questionable decision was possibly made under time pressure. It is unclear whether White can exploit his advantage in the arising rook endgame.   Instead  38.Nd2 !  allows White to preserve his lead while keeping all options open:  38...fxe5  39.Rxe5  Kd6  40.Ra5  += } 38... Nxc4 39. Rxc7+ Rxc7 40. Rxc4 fxe5 { The rook endgame that has arisen is quite interesting though completely unrelated to the topic of this chapter. I encourage the reader to study it, though I will limit myself to pointing out just a few variations. } 41. a4 { The option  41.Ke2  Ra7  42.Rc3  certainly deserves study. } 41... Ra7 42. a5 Rb7 43. Ke2 Rb5 { This manoeuvre is necessary. } 44. Kd3 c5 { Black is just in time; it is possible Zvjaginsev missed this when he played 38.Rxa7.   Instead, if Black simply waits with  44...Kd6  45.Kc3  Rb7   It is now too late for  45...c5 ?  46.Rxc5  Rxc5+  47.bxc5+  Kxc5  48.a6  Kb6  49.Kc4  Kxa6  50.Kc5  +-  46.Kb3  Rb5  47.Rc3  followed by  Kc4  and  Rd3  or  Rg3  when White is easily winning. } 45. Rxc5 Rxb4 46. Rc4 Rb3+ 47. Rc3 Rb2 48. g4 Ra2 49. Rc5 Kd6 50. Rb5 Ra4 { It is better to play  50...g5  to prevent White's pawns from advancing on the kingside. } 51. h4 Rd4+ 52. Ke3 Ra4 53. h5 Ra3+ 54. Kd2 Ra4 55. Kd3 Rd4+ 56. Ke3 Ra4 57. Rb7 Ra3+ 58. Kf2 Kc5 { Necessary is  58...Rxa5  59.Rxg7  Ra4  60.Rg6   60.Ke3  Ra3+  61.Ke2  Ra4 =  60...Rxe4  61.Kf3  Ra4  62.Rxh6  which seems risky for Black, but maybe it is just a draw. } 59. Rxg7 Rxa5 60. Rg6 Kd4 61. Rxh6 Kxe4 62. Rf6 { The rest is simple for White as the g- and h-pawns are unstoppable. } 62... Ra1 63. Kg2 Ra2+ 64. Rf2 Ra8 65. h6 Rh8 66. g5 Kd3 67. Rf7 Rg8 68. Rg7 { Final remarks  1. The reader should remember how threatening the ...b7-b5 break can be. The response cxb5 is often unsatisfactory as it gives up the d5-square permanently and makes White's queenside vulnerable.   2. Allowing Black to achieve the trades ...b5xc4 and b3xc4 enables Black to gain good counterplay along the b-file.   3. For this reason, the most memorable point in this game was Zvjaginsev's idea 15.Nf5 followed by 16.Ne3 and later recapturing with Nxc4. This turned the c6-pawn into a permanent weakness while preventing Black's further breaks with ...c6-c5 or ...a6-a5. } *

