{ @@HeaderStart@@Levon Aronian – Zong Yuan Zhao, Khanty-Mansiysk Olympiad 2010@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. This game illustrates White’s chances for a kingside attack.  2. The advance h2-h4 is typical and strong. Since White controls the centre he may carry out this advance without weakening his position. } 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bf4 a5 11. Nc3 Na6 12. Ne5 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nd5 14. Rad1 c6 { An alternative was  14...Nxf4+  15.gxf4  Bd6  16.e3  with an approximate balance. The reader should know that White’s doubled-pawns are more of a strength than a weakness in this position, as the central mass d4-e3-f2-f4 is solid, offers good control of the centre, and gives White an open g-file to press against Black’s king. } 15. Bc1 Nab4 { The alternative  15...Nxc3  only reinforces White’s centre after:  16.bxc3  Qd5+  17.f3  Qxc4  18.Nxc4  +=. } 16. e4 Nb6 17. Qe2 Nd7 18. Nf3 { Of course White does not wish to trade pieces in this position. } 18... Re8 19. h4 { This is a standard idea. Since White has better control of the centre, he can embark on kingside operations without fear. } 19... Qb6 20. Ng5 { The beginning of a very interesting and illustrative attack.   Instead, White could have fought for a small positional advantage after  20.Bf4 !?  Rad8  21.Nd2  += followed by  Nc4  with a slightly preferable position since  21...Qxd4 ?  is refuted by  22.Nc4  Qa7  23.Bc7  winning an exchange. } 20... h6 { Black decides to accept the challenge.   The more passive  20...Nf8  gives White a pleasant choice between  21.Be3  += with a stable advantage due to superior control of the centre   or  21.Qh5 !?  Bxg5  22.hxg5  with attacking prospects down the h-file. } 21. Rh1 Bf8 { The knight is immune as after  21...hxg5 ?  22.hxg5  Black’s pieces do not have the mobility to react quickly enough to the many threats down the h-file.  22...g6  23.Qf3 !  (threatening Rh8+ !)  23...f5   but not  23...Qd8 ?  24.Rh8+ !  Kxh8  25.Qxf7  followed by  Rh1#  24.gxf6  Bxf6  25.Rh6 !  With a decisive attack after either  25...Re7   or  25...Kg7  26.Qg4  Nf8  27.e5  Bd8  28.Ne4  26.Rxg6+  Rg7  27.Qh5  Qd8  28.Rh6 } 22. e5 { A logical continuation, allowing Nc3-e4 to bring another piece into the attack. Additionally, the e5-pawn is a powerful attacking tool, as it prevents Black from placing a knight on f6, protecting the kingside. } 22... f5 { This is the first and only mistake Black committed in the game.   The knight cannot be taken:  22...hxg5 ?  23.hxg5  g6  24.Qf3 !  The most precise, threatening  25.Rh8+  !.   Another path to victory is:  24.Ne4 !?  24...Bg7   The only move;   The following variation illustrates White’s attacking potential to its maximum:  24...Re7 ?!  25.Ne4  Bg7  26.Nf6+  Kf8  27.Rh7  Nd5  28.Rdh1  Rd8  29.Nxd7+  Rexd7  30.Qf6 !!  when checkmate is unstoppable.   Also  24...Qd8 ?  loses immediately to  25.Rh8+ !  Kxh8  26.Qxf7  followed by  Rh1.  25.Ne4  Here Black has many choices to attempt a defence, but they all fail in a similar fashion. As an example I offer the variation:  25...Red8  26.Nf6+  Kf8   26...Nxf6 ?  only makes things easier:  27.gxf6  Bf8  28.Qg4  followed by Qh4-h8 mating.  27.Rh7  Nd5  28.Nh5 !  The key move, Black is defenceless after:  28...gxh5  29.g6  f5  30.Bh6 !  Bxh6  31.Qxh5  Bg7  32.Rxg7 !  With forced mate.   Instead of  22...f5 ?  Black should have reacted in the centre with  22...c5 !  undermining the d4-e5 chain and bringing the queen into the game with  ...Qb6-c6.  Then  23.Nf3 !?  with a complicated game.   the obstinate  23.Qh5 ?  is met by  23...g6  24.Qf3  hxg5  25.h5  Qc6  when Black has more than enough resources to defend. } 23. Qh5 Re7 24. Qg6 { +- Forcing Black to open the h-file thus allowing the entrance of White’s forces. } 24... hxg5 25. hxg5 { The threat is Rh4, Rdh1 and Rh8#. } 25... c5 { Black cannot escape with  25...Ree8  due to  26.Rh8+ !  Kxh8  27.Qf7  followed by  Rh1#. } 26. Nb5 { Intending to follow with Nd6 and Qh7#. } 26... Qc6+ { Again  26...Ree8  loses to  27.Rh8+ !  Kxh8  28.Qf7  with forced mate. } 27. f3 cxd4 28. Qh7+ { Black resigns, since after  28...Kf7  29.Nd6+  the queen is lost.  Final remarks  1. White’s kingside attack can be very powerful and requires extreme precision from Black’s defence.  2. This flank attack should have been met with the conceptually correct central break 22...c5 !.  3. In retrospect, it might have been objectively better to play 20.Bf4 securing a small positional edge, though practical chances should not be ignored. It is true that Black had one way to maintain equality against White’s attack; but how strong does a player need to be in order to find such a precise continuation? The strong GM Zhao was unable to defend, so I believe White’s attack is possibly the strongest continuation, at least on a practical level. } *

