{ @@HeaderStart@@Alexander Morozevich vs. Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, Beijing 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. Black needs to achieve either ...c6-c5 or ...e6-e5 in order to release his position.  2. This game illustrates how White can break through Black’s passive defence if neither of these breaks is achieved. } 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. d4 c6 6. O-O d5 7. Qb3 dxc4 8. Qxc4 Qd5 { Having a half-point lead in the Beijing Grand Prix tournament, Mamedyarov chose this rare sideline, offering to get the queens off the board. } 9. Nbd2 { And surprisingly, Morozevich  (a well-known tactician)  responds with another rare move  (a novelty after only 9 moves)  accepting entry into an endgame.   Previously avoiding the exchange with  9.Qa4 !?  had been played with success. } 9... Qxc4 10. Nxc4 { This is a key moment in the game and deserves some comment. With the queens off the board, Black is very unlikely to face a mating attack like we saw in the previous game. But does this mean Black can secure a draw? Not necessarily. Neutralizing White’s space advantage is not easy even without queens, and the key question is whether Black will be able to free his position with ...c6-c5 or ...e7-e5 in order to dispute White’s central dominance. If that is not the case, White will enjoy a lasting positional advantage and the defensive task will require Black to constantly calculate how to defend against possible breaks, giving him little hope in a practical game where errors cannot be completely avoided. } 10... Be6 { The alternative  10...Nbd7  does not seem to change things much after:  11.b3  Nb6   Black cannot break in the centre with  11...c5 ?  12.Ba3 !  as Black will have a serious struggle to complete his development without losing material, for example  12...Nd5  13.Rac1  cxd4  14.Nxd4  Bxd4  15.Bxd5  Bf6  16.Rfd1  ±  12.Na5 !  Avoiding the exchange of pieces, and preventing Black from developing his bishop due to the pressure on  b7.  12...Rd8  13.Ba3  Nbd5  14.Rac1  += This is similar to the game. } 11. b3 Bd5 { The alternative  11...Ne4  12.Ba3  Re8   the break  12...c5 ?  fails due to  13.Nfe5 !  ±  13.Rac1  is similar to the game.   The try  11...Bxc4  12.bxc4  Ne4  (hoping for ...c6-c5)  is met by  13.Rb1 !  b6   or  13...Nc3 ?!  14.Rxb7  Nxe2+  15.Kh1  Nxd4  16.Nxd4  Bxd4  17.Rxe7  ±  14.Bf4  += followed by  Ne5  with a comfortable edge. } 12. Ba3 Re8 13. Rac1 Nbd7 14. Na5 { The knight will be ideally located on a5, pressuring the b7-pawn and preventing ...b7-b6 due to Nxc6. } 14... Rab8 15. Rfd1 { It becomes clear that Black will not easily be able to dispute White’s centre, thus falling into a permanently inferior position. } 15... Bf8 { The break  15...e5 ?  fails due to  16.Nxe5  Nxe5  17.dxe5  Rxe5  18.Bd6  winning the exchange.   Nor does it help to play:  15...Ne4  16.Nd2  (White needs to trade some pieces in order to be able to push the desired e2-e4 gaining central control)  16...Ndf6   or  16...Nxd2  17.Bxd5  cxd5  18.Rxd2  += when the character of the game has changed, but White retains his advantage by controlling the only open file  17.Nxe4  Nxe4  18.f3  Nd6  19.e4  Be6  White dominates and may continue to improve his position with  20.Bc5  Nc8  21.f4  Nb6  22.h3  += intending to gain even more space with g3-g4.   The attempt  15...Bxf3  16.Bxf3  Bf8  intending to follow up with  ...e7-e5  can be met by  17.Bb2  e5  18.dxe5  Nxe5  19.Bg2  where the pair of bishops and excellent piece coordination secure an advantage for White, for example:  19...Bb4  20.Nc4  Nxc4  21.Bxf6  Nd6  22.Kf1  += } 16. Ne5 Bxg2 { Keeping more pieces on the board with  16...Be6 ?!  is unlikely to help Black due to his lack of space. } 17. Kxg2 e6 { Worse is  17...Nxe5  18.dxe5  Nd5  19.e4  Nb6  20.Rc3  followed by  Rcd3  controlling the only open file. } 18. Bxf8 Kxf8 19. Nec4 Ke7 { But not  19...e5 ?  due to  20.Nd6  Re7  21.Naxb7  and wins. } 20. b4 { Preventing the break ...c6-c5. } 20... Rec8 { 20...Nb6  21.Ne5  Nfd7  22.Naxc6+  bxc6  23.Nxc6+  Kd6  24.Nxb8  Rxb8  25.e4  ± } 21. a3 g5 { A good decision, as Black needs to claim some space in order not to be asphyxiated by White’s potential expansion with e2-e4, f2-f4, h2-h3 and g3-g4.   White should constantly calculate liberation attempts, such as  21...b6 ?!  22.Nb3  c5 ?!  but fortunately for White, in this case, this attempt is refuted by  23.dxc5  bxc5  24.Nca5 !  ± winning material. } 22. Nb2 { A prophylactic move, preventing freeing attempts with ...b7-b6 followed by ...c6-c5 as mentioned in the previous note. } 22... Ne8 23. Nd3 { Note how both knights are ideally arranged to pressure Black’s queenside and prevent liberation. } 23... f5 24. h4 { Gaining control of the f4-square. } 24... g4 { But not  24...gxh4 ?  25.Rh1 !  Nef6   even worse is  25...hxg3 ?  26.Rxh7+  Kd8  27.Nf4  26.Rxh4  ± and the h7-pawn has become a serious weakness.   A bad idea would be  24...h6 ?!  25.hxg5  hxg5  26.Rh1  Nef6  27.Ne5  → when only White will take advantage of the open h-file. } 25. Nf4 Nef6 26. Rc2 Nd5 27. Nd3 Rf8 28. e3 Rfe8 29. Re1 { Speculating on a potential e3-e4. Note how Black constantly needs to calculate how to defend against potential threats, while White can choose his moves almost randomly. A practical strategy for White is to continuously present Black with potential threats, but without carrying out any of them until the right time has come. Often White will continue to use this strategy until Black commits a serious mistake, or finds himself in time trouble, and only then will White embark on decisive action. } 29... N5f6 { Preventing e3-e4.   To illustrate how delicate Black’s position is, note how the natural  29...Rf8  falls into trouble after  30.Rb2 !  (threatening Nc5 winning a pawn)  30...Rfc8  31.e4 !  fxe4  32.Rxe4  ± and Black is on the verge of losing. } 30. Rb1 { Threatening Nc5 winning a pawn. } 30... Rec8 31. Rbc1 Rd8 { More stubborn was  31...Nb6. } 32. a4 { ± Preparing a break with b4-b5 in order to invade Black’s camp via the c-file. } 32... Ne4 { Mamedyarov miscalculates in an already very difficult situation.   The correct defence was  32...Ne8 !  33.b5  cxb5  34.axb5  Nd6  35.Rc7  Nxb5  36.Rxb7  Rxb7  37.Nxb7  Rb8  38.Na5  ± though Black’s position is full of weaknesses. } 33. b5 cxb5 34. Rc7 { This would have been prevented if Black’s knight had been on e8. } 34... Nd6 { 34...bxa4 ?  loses to  35.Nxb7  Re8  36.Ne5  Nef6  37.Nc6+. } 35. Nc5 bxa4 { A better defence was  35...Ne8  36.Rxb7  Rxb7  37.Ncxb7  Ra8  38.axb5  though Black’s position is practically lost. } 36. Ncxb7 Nxb7 37. Nxb7 Rf8 38. R1c6 { +- Black’s position falls apart due to the threat of 39.Nc5. } 38... Rf7 39. Nc5 Ke8 40. Rxe6+ Kd8 41. Rec6 { Black resigns as the a7- and a4-pawns will soon be lost.  Final remarks  1. If Black wishes to equalize, it is absolutely necessary to find a break by either ...e6-e5 or ...c6-c5.   2. The endgame starting on move 19 was nearly lost on a practical level. The reason is that Black could not create any counterplay or find any way to equalize. Meanwhile, White could move his pieces around the entire board, speculating with multiple threats. Even Super-GMs like Mamedyarov cannot avoid decisive mistakes under such circumstances. } *

