{ @@HeaderStart@@Jon Ludvig Hammer – Magnus Carlsen, Sandnes 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. This game is an example of a position in which Black is likely to achieve the ...c6-c5 break.  2. After the break is achieved, Black has to parry some threats. But once these threats are neutralized, it is Black who plays for the advantage. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 a5 7. Qc2 Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 c6 9. a4 { The alternative  9.Ne5  can lead to a complicated position after  9...b5  10.a4 !?  when White has pressure on the queenside and centre, in compensation for Black’s extra pawn   or  10.Nxc6  Qc7 = } 9... Ne4 10. Qc2 Nd6 { Black will not give up the c4-pawn without trading another piece to alleviate his space problem. } 11. Nbd2 Na6 12. Nxc4 Nb4 13. Nxd6+ Qxd6 14. Qd2 { We have reached the position of interest, and the reader should pay close attention to the differences between this game and the previous one. In the current game, two minor pieces are off the board already, decreasing Black’s space problem. In addition, the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 greatly favour Black, as they give a strong square for the knight on b4 and have eliminated White’s chances to expand on the queenside in the future with the usual b2-b4. Finally, Black has a concrete plan, which is ...b7-b6, ...Ba6  (or ...Bb7)  followed by placing the rooks in the centre and pushing ...c6-c5. Unlike the previous game, White lacks pieces to prevent such liberation. For all the above reasons, the reader should understand that Black has chosen correctly when he decided to play this pawn structure. } 14... O-O 15. O-O Rd8 16. Rfd1 b6 17. Qc3 { The alternative  17.Ne5  is not enough to prevent Black’s liberation either:  17...Ba6  18.Rac1  Rac8  19.Nc4  Bxc4  20.Rxc4  c5  and Black has fully equalized. } 17... Ba6 18. Rd2 { If  18.e4 ?!  Black is ready to break in the centre with  18...c5 !  =+ taking the lead, since  19.dxc5 ?  loses to  19...Qxd1+  20.Rxd1  Rxd1+  21.Ne1  Nc2 !  22.Qxc2  Rxe1+  23.Bf1  Bxf1. } 18... Rac8 19. Rad1 { Placing both rooks on the d-file is correct, as White needs to fight for the initiative once the ...c6-c5 break comes. } 19... Qe7 { Preparing c6-c5.   Of course not  19...c5 ?  20.dxc5. } 20. h4 c5 { Black achieves the desired break, disputing White’s control of the centre.   Also possible was  20...Rd6 !?  in order to further prepare the  ...c6-c5  break. } 21. dxc5 Rd5 { An interesting intermediate move, preparing ...Rcxc5.   Another option was:  21...Rxd2  22.Qxd2  Qxc5  23.Ne5 !?  This is White’s only chance to fight for an advantage, but after  23...Nd5  there is nothing special for White, for example  24.Bxd5  Qxd5  25.Qxd5  exd5  26.e3  f6  27.Nd7  Rc2  with a level game. } 22. Rxd5 { A good alternative was:  22.Ng5 !?  Rcxc5  23.Qe3  Rxd2  24.Qxd2  (threatening Qd8)  24...Rc8  25.Qd7  Qxd7  26.Rxd7  Bxe2  27.Nxf7  += } 22... Nxd5 23. Qe5 Qxc5 { Black has fully equalized. } 24. Bh3 { Threatening Bxe6.   If White tries  24.Nd4  threatening  Nxe6  , Black equalizes with the forced line  24...Nc3 !  25.Qxc5  bxc5  26.bxc3  cxd4  27.cxd4  Bxe2   Or  24.Ng5  Nf6 !  25.Qxc5  bxc5  26.e3  Rb8  with mutual chances. } 24... Re8 25. Nd4 { Reinforcing the threat on e6.   Alternatively,  25.Ng5  Nf6  26.Qxc5  bxc5  with a level endgame } 25... Kf8 { A curious move. } 26. Bf1 { Or  26.e4  Nb4  27.Qxc5+  bxc5  28.Nb5  Ke7  with a balanced endgame. } 26... Rc8 27. Nb5 { This mistake is hard to understand.   Better was  27.Nf5  Nf6  28.Qxc5+  Rxc5  29.Rd8+  Ne8  30.Nd6  Ke7  31.Rxe8+  Kxd6  32.Rb8  Rc6  with approximate equality, though I find Black’s position slightly preferable since his king is very close to White’s weakened queenside.   On the other hand  27.e4 ?  is bad:  27...Bxf1  28.exd5   or  28.Rxf1  Nf6  29.Qxc5+  Rxc5  ∓  28...Bc4  ∓ winning a pawn. } 27... Bxb5 28. axb5 Nf6 { Now White’s position becomes very difficult due to the weak b2- and b5-pawns.   The pawn is untouchable:  28...Qxb5 ?  29.e4  when White wins the knight after  29...Qa4  30.b3 !  (the only move)  30...Qxb3  31.Rd3  followed by  exd5  since here  31...Nc3 ?  allows mate by:  32.Qd6+  Kg8   32...Ke8  33.Qd7+  33.Qd8+  Rxd8  34.Rxd8# } 29. Qd6+ { 29.Qf4  Qxb5  ∓ } 29... Ke8 { Also possible was  29...Qxd6  30.Rxd6  Nd5  31.e4  Ke7  32.e5  Rc1  ∓ followed by  ...Rb1xb2  when the a5-pawn should decide the game. } 30. Qd3 Qd5 { ∓ Forcing the trade of queens under ideal circumstances, as Black’s king is already closer to the battlefield, and White’s b-pawns are very weak. } 31. Qxd5 exd5 32. e4 { White is desperately looking for counterplay. Passive defence with  32.Rd2  does not help:  32...Ke7  33.e3  Rc1  34.f3  Kd6  35.Kf2  Kc5  ∓ when White’s queenside weaknesses and Black’s strong king should tell. } 32... Rc2 { A good practical decision, depriving White of counterplay.   Technically  32...dxe4  works, but White gains some counterplay with  33.Rd6. } 33. e5 { Preferable was  33.exd5  Rxb2  ∓ when Black’s a5-pawn is much more dangerous than the isolated d5-pawn. } 33... Ne4 34. Rxd5 Rxb2 { The a5-pawn now decides the game. } 35. Rd4 Rb4 36. Rd1 { Instead  36.Rxb4 ?  axb4  loses immediately, since White must give up his bishop for the pawn. } 36... a4 37. Bg2 Nc3 38. Bc6+ Ke7 39. Rd7+ Ke6 40. Ra7 Kxe5 { White resigns since the a4-pawn cannot be stopped without great material loss.  Final remarks  1. The main message of this game is that White cannot really hope for an advantage if he is unable to prevent a ...c6-c5 break.  2. A crucial role was played by the weakening move a2-a4 and Black’s knight on b4, which substantially limited the coordination of White’s pieces. For example, on moves 17-19 White would have liked to play Rac1, but could not due to ...Na2 winning an exchange. } *

