{ @@HeaderStart@@Wang Yue – Magnus Carlsen, Medias 2010@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates how White’s d4-pawn could become vulnerable, and how Black makes use of it. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bd2 Bg7 6. e4 Nb6 7. Be3 { An opening book would say this is really a Grünfeld position and this is true. However, from a positional standpoint, the structure and character of this game more closely resembles the Queen’s Gambit Accepted. } 7... O-O 8. Bb5 { This standard opening move prevents Black from developing a knight to c6. } 8... Be6 9. Nge2 c6 10. Bd3 Nc4 11. Bxc4 Bxc4 12. O-O Nd7 13. Qd2 Qa5 14. Rfd1 Rad8 15. Bh6 Bxe2 16. Nxe2 Qxd2 17. Bxd2 Nb6 { We have reached the position we are truly interested in. The reader should notice how well Black has conducted this game. He managed to trade two minor pieces and the queen, solving the space problem, and now is ready to exert pressure against the d4-pawn. White’s pieces are poorly located to defend the vulnerable centre. } 18. Bc3 { Other bishop moves only further risk the d4-pawn.   If  18.e5  , blocking the bishop on  g7  to protect the d4-pawn, then after  18...f6 !?  19.f4  Nc4  20.Bc3  Rd7  =+ Black enjoys a pleasant positional edge.   The try  18.Be3  is met by:  18...Nc4 !  19.b3  Nxe3  20.fxe3  e5 !  =+ } 18... Rd7 { Preparing to double rooks in order to increase the pressure against d4.   A strong alternative was:  18...Na4 !?  19.Rd2  f5 !  20.exf5   Supporting the centre with  20.f3  is not possible due to  20...Bh6 !  21.Rd3  e5 !  ∓ creating strong threats, for example  22.Rad1 ?   or  22.d5  cxd5  23.exd5  Rfe8  ∓  22...fxe4  23.fxe4  exd4  24.Nxd4  Nc5  25.Rh3  Bg7  winning material by force.  20...Rxf5  21.Rad1  Rfd5  =+ With definite pressure. } 19. b3 f5 { Challenging White’s central control.   Another option was  19...Rfd8  pressuring the d4-pawn and now:  20.Rd2  Na8 !  A key manoeuvre.  21.Rad1  Nc7  (heading to either b5 or e6)  22.f3  f5 !?  =+ gives better chances to Black due to White’s vulnerable central pawns. } 20. f3 { Maintaining control of the d5-square.   If  20.exf5  Rxf5  White’s centre is quite vulnerable, for example:  21.Rac1  Nd5  22.Bd2  Rf8  23.g3  Nc7  24.Be3  Rfd8  =+ followed by  ...Nb5  and potential breaks  ...e7-e5  or  ...c6-c5. } 20... Rfd8 21. Re1 fxe4 { Now it is too late for  21...Na8  hoping for  ...Nc7-b5  , because of  22.d5 !  Bxc3  23.Nxc3  cxd5  24.Nxd5  with a level game. } 22. fxe4 e5 { This is a break to be remembered. It forces the creation of an isolated e-pawn. } 23. dxe5 Rd3 { Probably not the most precise.   Slightly better was  23...Re8 !?  24.Rad1  Bxe5  25.Bxe5  Rxe5  26.Nc3  Kf7  =+ when the e4-pawn is somewhat vulnerable. } 24. g3 { A severe imprecision allowing Black to take the lead.   White could have held on to approximate equality after  24.Bb2  Re8  25.Rad1  Re3  26.Nc1  Rxe1+  27.Rxe1  Nd7  28.Nd3  Nxe5. } 24... Nd7 25. e6 { Worsening the situation.   A better continuation was  25.Ba5  Nxe5   or  25...b6  26.Nf4 !  26.Bxd8  Nf3+  27.Kf2  Nxe1  28.Rxe1  Rxd8  =+ though Black has good chances to fight for the win. } 25... Bxc3 26. Nxc3 Ne5 { =+ Now Black has obtained the kind of position one dreams of when playing ...f7-f5 followed by ...e7-e5. The e4-pawn is a clear weakness and Black will follow with ...Kf8-e7xe6 with a clear advantage. } 27. Red1 Kf8 28. Rac1 { 28.Rxd3  Rxd3  29.Na4  does not help because of the simple:  29...Ke7  30.Nc5  Rd2 !  31.Nxb7  Nf3+  32.Kf1  Nxh2+  33.Ke1  Nf3+  34.Kf1  Kxe6  ∓ } 28... Ke7 29. Rxd3 Rxd3 30. Rc2 Nf3+ 31. Kf1 Nd4 32. Rc1 Kxe6 { White’s position is desperate despite having equal material, because of the chronic weakness of the e4-pawn. } 33. Rd1 { Other options are worse.   Another try was  33.Ke1  Ke5  34.Nd1  b6   but not  34...Kxe4 ??  35.Nf2+  35.Rc4  c5  36.Nf2  Rf3  ∓ and Black will progress slowly with  ...h7-h5  ,  ...g6-g5-g4  ,  ...a7-a5  , etc. White’s position is hopeless. } 33... Rxc3 { An interesting option was  33...Rf3+ !?  34.Ke1   or  34.Kg2  Rxc3  35.Rxd4  Rc2+  36.Kf3  Rxa2  -+  34...Ke5  35.Ne2  c5  36.Nxd4  cxd4  ∓ with a practically winning position. } 34. Rxd4 Rc2 35. a4 { As Rogozenko suggests, the try  35.Ra4  does not help because after  35...a6  36.h4  Ke5  White is in zugzwang and lost. For example  37.Ke1   or  37.Kg1  Re2   or, worst of all,  37.Rb4 ?  b5  followed by  ...c6-c5  37...Rg2 } 35... Rxh2 { Black has a healthy extra pawn, and won this endgame without difficulty after: } 36. a5 Rh5 37. b4 Rh2 38. a6 b5 { Keeping the queenside pawns healthy. } 39. e5 Ra2 40. Rd6+ Kxe5 41. Rxc6 Kf5 42. Rc7 Rxa6 43. Rxh7 Kg4 44. Kf2 Ra2+ 45. Ke3 g5 46. Rg7 Rb2 47. Rxa7 Kxg3 { Final remarks  1. In the endgame, once e3-e4 has been played, the d4-pawn can become an object of attack.  2. The reader should remember that pressuring the d4-pawn will not always work. It works particularly well in this game because Black’s bishop was on g7, and because White’s pieces were poorly placed to begin with.  3. The break ...f7-f5 is an important move in Black’s strategy, undermining the control of the d5-square.  4. The idea of ...f7-f5, followed by trading pawns on e4 and playing ...e7-e5, is thematic and strategically sound, as it turns the e4-pawn into a permanent weakness. } *

