{ @@HeaderStart@@Nicolai Getz – Simen Agdestein, Fagernes 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. It is bad for White to have a Carlsbad structure with the dark-squared bishop inside the chain.  2. This game illustrates how Black will easily gain control of the e4-square and later develop a kingside attack. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 c6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd2 O-O 8. cxd5 { This natural-looking move is actually a serious opening imprecision that has been played more than 30 times – with poor results.   More common is  8.Bd3. } 8... exd5 { Of course Black retakes with ...exd5 heading into a Carlsbad structure under favourable circumstances. The reader should remember the reason: White’s dark-squared bishop is inside the pawn chain and, compared to a powerful bishop on f4 or g5, it is rather useless on d2. } 9. Bd3 { The very same Agdestein  (Black in the current game)   went for this line 20 years before, though he continued  9.O-O-O  Re8  10.Bd3  c5 !  when Black has a preferable position due to his strong initiative on the queenside, as in the game Agdestein – Shirov, Gausdal 1992. } 9... Re8 10. O-O { Turning the position into an isolated-queen-pawn type with  10.e4 ?  fails to  10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  Nxe4  12.Bxe4  Nf6  and White loses a piece. } 10... Qe7 { Preventing White’s liberation with e3-e4.   Instead  10...Nf8 ?!  allows  11.e4 !  dxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  with level chances in a typical isolani position. } 11. Rae1 { Trapping the rook on f1 only makes matters worse, but there are no good suggestions for White anyway.   Attempting to develop the standard queenside plan with b2-b4-b5 is too slow, for example  11.a3  Ne4  12.b4  Ndf6  13.h3   or  13.b5  Bg4 !  when Black is already creating threats  13...Bf5  =+ when Black has comfortable control of the e4-square and good potential for a kingside attack, while White has little to say on the queenside. } 11... Ne4 { Black’s advantage is indisputable. } 12. Bc1 Ndf6 13. h3 Bd7 { The reader should note how little White has to hope for. } 14. Nd2 { Attempting to remove Black’s knight from e4.   It does not help to play  14.Bxe4 ?!  as it gives Black a pleasant choice between  14...Nxe4   or  14...dxe4 !?  15.Nd2  Rac8  ∓ followed by  ...c6-c5  and potentially  ...Rxc5-g5.  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.Nd2  Qh4  ∓ threatening  ...Bxh3  with a very dangerous attack } 14... Rac8 { A very healthy and powerful move, preparing the idea ...c6-c5 to incorporate Black’s rook into the attack.   Another option was  14...Bb8  aiming to play  15...Qd6  with threats along b8-h2, but probably Black does not want to trap his rook on  a8. } 15. a3 { The value of Black’s 14th move is illustrated in the variation  15.Ndxe4 ?  dxe4  16.Bc4  b5  17.Bb3  c5 !  and if  18.dxc5  Rxc5  followed by  ...b5-b4  winning a piece, or  ...Rg5  with a crushing attack. } 15... Bb8 { Preparing ...Qd6 to threaten ...Qh2#.   The try  15...c5 ?  fails to  16.Nxd5 !  Nxd5  17.Nxe4 } 16. Ndxe4 { The decisive mistake: White underestimates Black’s attacking chances.   Preferable was  16.b4  Qd6  17.f4  Bf5  (in order to trade light-squared bishops)  18.Bb2  Nxd2  19.Qxd2  Bxd3  20.Qxd3  Ne4  21.Nxe4  Rxe4  ∓ when Black can slowly improve his position, for example with  ...f7-f5  ,  ...Rce8  and eventually  ...g7-g5. } 16... dxe4 17. Bc4 b5 18. Ba2 c5 { Bringing the rook into the game.   Another option was:  18...Qd6 !?  19.f4   or  19.g3  Bxh3  -+  19...exf3  20.Rxf3  Qh2+  21.Kf1  Bg3  -+ There is nothing better than giving up the exchange. } 19. dxc5 Qe5 20. f4 exf3 21. Rxf3 Qh2+ 22. Kf2 { 22.Kf1  Bc6  23.e4  Bg3  forces White to give up the exchange:  24.Rxg3  Qxg3  -+ } 22... Rxc5 { White is simply defenceless against the multiple threats, such as ...Bc6 or ...Ne4+. } 23. Rd1 Bc6 24. e4 Nxe4+ 25. Qxe4 { 25.Nxe4  Rxc2+  and wins. } 25... Bxe4 26. Nxe4 Rc2+ 27. Ke3 Rxe4+ 28. Kd3 { Also hopeless is  28.Kxe4  Qe5+  29.Kd3  Qe2+  30.Kd4  Qxd1+. } 28... Rcc4 { Final remarks  1. Having his bishop locked inside the pawn chain sentenced White to an outright inferior position.  2. White’s chances of counterplay were practically non-existent after 11...Ne4.   3. Black’s move ...Rac8 was somewhat unexpected, but very important, as the break ...c6-c5 played a crucial role in many variations.  I hope this game leaves a strong impression on the reader. White’s dark-squared bishop must be outside the pawn chain for White to have a chance in the Carlsbad structure.    Making a Caro-Kann analogy to this example, after the sequence  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  4.Bd3  Nc6  5.c3  it would be absolutely incorrect to play  5...e6 ?  as it locks the bishop inside the pawn chain, allowing White to gain a powerful attack as Black did in the previous game. } *

