{ @@HeaderStart@@Gilberto Milos – Marc Narciso Dublan, Mexico City 2010@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates how White can carry out the standard minority attack in the Carlsbad, and how to attack the weaknesses once they are created. } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 Be7 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. h3 O-O 9. Qc2 Re8 10. Nf3 Nf8 11. Bf4 { Hence it makes sense for Black to trade it with: } 11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. O-O { This is a standard set-up for this pawn structure; in fact there are over 100 games in my database with this exact position. } 13... Be6 { Another option was:  13...Qe7  14.Rab1  Ne4  15.b4  a6  16.a4   If  16.Bxe4  dxe4  17.Nd2  Bf5  chances are level. Black may continue with  ...Ng6-h4  aiming for a kingside attack.  16...Bf5  17.b5  Nxc3  18.Qxc3  Bxd3  19.Qxd3  cxb5  20.axb5  a5  Black has a playable position, though the d5-pawn is a small weakness. } 14. Rab1 N6d7 { Probably better was:  14...a5  15.a3  N8d7  16.Rfc1   Black is ready to meet  16.b4 ?!  with  16...b5 !  when he achieves reasonable counterplay associated with  ...Nb6-c4.  White is unable to take advantage of the weakness of the c6-pawn:  17.Rfc1  Nb6  18.Qb3  axb4  19.Qxb4  Qxb4  20.axb4  Nc4  With a level game.  16...h6  17.Na4  White is getting ready to play b2-b4.  17...Ne4 !  The right moment for this reaction.  18.Nd2   It is not possible to grab the pawn with  18.Bxe4  dxe4  19.Qxe4 ?  due to  19...Bb3  winning the knight.  18...Bf5  19.Bxe4  Rxe4 !  20.Nxe4  Bxe4  21.Qd1  Qg6  22.Qf1  Black has a comfortable position, and agreed to a draw in the game Krivoshey – Klovans, Germany 1997. } 15. b4 Nb6 16. Nd2 Rad8 { Black plays without a clear plan, and misses his chance to play the standard ...a7-a6 defensive move.   It was not too late for Black to play:  16...a6  17.a4  g6   but not  17...Nc4 ?!  18.Bxc4  dxc4  19.b5 !  += as the c4-pawn is permanently weakened  18.Rfc1 !?  += The b4-b5 break is coming sooner or later, but at least Black will only have to deal with one weakness – probably the c6-pawn – instead of two weaknesses as in the game.   It is premature to play  18.b5 ?!  axb5  19.axb5  c5 !  20.dxc5  Qxc5  when Black has enough counterplay to compensate for the isolated queen pawn, because of the open a- and c-files, as well as the c4-square for one of Black’s knights. } 17. Ne2 { White wants to prevent Black from responding ...c6-c5 against the break b4-b5.   An interesting alternative was  17.b5  c5  18.dxc5  Qxc5  19.Nf3  Rc8  20.Rbc1  += where White enjoys a slightly favourable version of the isolani. As we studied in the game Vitiugov – Bologan from Chapter 1, the absence of Black’s dark-squared bishop deprives him of useful counterplay. Compare this to the note after Black’s 16th move, and see how in this case the a-file is now closed, limiting Black’s options. } 17... Bc8 { Now it is too late for  17...a6  due to:  18.Nb3 !  Qe7   the tempting  18...Nc4 ?  fails after  19.Nc5 !  Qe7   19...Na3 ?  is no help:  20.Qb2  Nxb1  21.Nxb7  Qc7  22.Nxd8  and wins  20.Bxc4  dxc4  21.Nxe6  Qxe6  22.Nf4  Qe4  23.Qxc4  ± winning a pawn  19.Nc5  Bc8  20.a4  ± leaving Black unprepared to meet b4-b5. } 18. b5 { White achieves the b4-b5 break under optimal conditions, creating at least one serious weakness in Black’s queenside. } 18... cxb5 19. Rxb5 { The d5-pawn is now very weak. } 19... Bd7 20. Ra5 Nc8 { A better defence was  20...Ra8  21.Qc5  Qxc5  22.dxc5  Nc8  23.Rb1  Bc6  24.Nd4  Ne7  += and Black seems to hold for a while.   But not  20...a6 ?  21.Rb1  followed by  Qb3  , when Black’s queenside is about to collapse. } 21. Nf4 Bc6 22. Bb5 { Clarifying the position on the queenside; the positional threat is Bxc6 forcing the creation of a very weak pawn on c6. } 22... Ne6 { It is no better to play:  22...Bxb5  23.Rxb5  Nb6  24.a4  threatening a4-a5 winning the d5-pawn.  24...a6   or  24...Rc8  25.Qb3  ±  25.Rb3  ± Now the b7-pawn becomes a serious target. } 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. Nd3 { This position deserves some comment. Since Black decided not to play ...a7-a6 earlier in the game, both the a2- and a7-pawns remain present. This plays a crucial role, as Black needs to worry about protecting both the a7- and c6-pawns. } 24... Rd7 25. Rc1 Rc7 26. Qc3 Nb6 27. Nc5 { To be followed by Na6-b4 in order to pressure the c6-pawn. } 27... Qd8 { Of course not  27...Nxc5 ??  28.dxc5. } 28. Na6 Rc8 29. Qa3 Re7 30. Nb4 { Note how both the a7-pawn and the c6-pawn are under attack; Black’s defence has collapsed. } 30... Qd6 { A better defence was  30...Rec7  31.Rxa7  c5  32.Rxc7  Rxc7  33.dxc5  Nxc5  ± though White has an extra pawn for no compensation. } 31. Rxc6 { +- A nice tactical blow in a strategically winning position. } 31... Rxc6 32. Nxc6 Qxa3 { Not  32...Qxc6 ??  33.Qxe7  and White wins at once. } 33. Rxa3 Rc7 34. Nb4 { White is a pawn up, while the d5- and a7-pawns remain serious weaknesses.   There is nothing wrong with  34.Nxa7  , though White needs to calculate the consequences of  34...Rc1+  35.Kh2  Rc2. } 34... Kf8 35. Kf1 Ke8 36. Ra5 Nc4 { Passive defence with  36...Rd7  does not enable the position to be held, for example:  37.Ke2  g6   37...Kd8 ?!  38.Rxa7  winning a second pawn  38.Kd3  Nd8  39.Nb1  followed by  Nc3  winning easily. } 37. Nxc4 dxc4 { The passed pawn on c4 is simply another weakness in Black’s camp. } 38. Ke2 Rb7 39. a3 Nc7 40. Kd2 Nb5 41. Kc2 Kd7 { 41...Nxa3+  fails to help after  42.Rxa3  Rxb4  43.Rxa7  as the c4-pawn is practically lost, say after  Ra2  and  Kc3. } 42. Ra6 h5 43. Nd5 h4 44. Nc3 Nd6 { Or  44...Nxc3  45.Kxc3  Rc7  46.e4  is winning. } 45. e4 { White has arranged his pieces in harmony and suppressed all counterplay; the rest is very simple. } 45... f6 46. f3 Nc8 47. Na4 Ke8 48. Rc6 Ne7 49. Rxc4 Ng6 50. Nc5 Rc7 51. Kb3 Nf4 52. Rc2 a5 53. Kc4 g5 54. d5 Rc8 55. Kd4 Rb8 56. e5 fxe5+ 57. Kxe5 Rb1 58. Ne6 Nd3+ 59. Kf6 Kd7 60. Nxg5 Rb3 61. Nf7 Ne1 62. Re2 Nxg2 63. Ne5+ { Final remarks  1. Black could have faced fewer problems if he had played ...a7-a6 at the right time. Then after a future b4-b5, Black would have had some chances to protect the weak c6-pawn.  2. The sequence of moves before White’s tactical blow 31.Rxc6 would not have worked so easily for White if Black did not have a weak a7-pawn. Essentially this was not a tactical mistake, but the consequence of a prior positional mistake   not playing  14...a5  , or not playing  15...a6  or  16...a6  . } *

