{ @@HeaderStart@@Radoslaw Wojtaszek – Ildar Khairullin, Aix-les-Bains 2011@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:   This game explains how White may proceed with a queenside attack if Black’s queenside pawns are arranged as a7-b6-c7 instead of the typical a7-b7-c6. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. e3 Bb7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5 8. cxd5 exd5 9. a3 Bd6 10. b4 { Everything is being played according to modern theory; in fact there are over 250 games with this position. One should pay close attention to Black’s pawn structure on the queenside. The most typical Carlsbad structure has pawns on a6-b7-c6-d5, which makes the b4-b5 break quite powerful. In this case, it might seem that White has little to hope for since b4-b5 does not create any weak pawns, but this is not quite the case. White’s plan is to first gain some space on the queenside with b4-b5 and a3-a4, weakening the c6-square and  'isolating” the d5-pawn, and then either play Ba3xd6 in order to weaken the c7-pawn, or blow up the centre with e3-e4. In both cases, Black’s counterplay is associated with placing a knight on e4 and then creating a kingside attack, possibly through ...f7-f5 and ...g6-g5, as illustrated in the note to Black’s 10th move. } 10... a6 { An alternative was:  10...a5  11.b5  Nbd7  12.Bd2 ?!   instead I would have recommended  12.Qb3  followed by a3-a4 and  Ba3  trading Black’s dark-squared bishop to weaken the c7-pawn  12...Ne4  A good decision; it is crucial for Black to gain control of the e4-square, not only to prevent an eventual e3-e4 break, but also to gain attacking prospects on the kingside.  13.a4  Qe7  14.h3  f5  Reinforcing the knight on  e4  and increasing the attacking chances against White’s monarch.  15.Qc2  Ndf6  16.Rac1  Rae8  17.Ne2  g5  Black obtained a dangerous attack in Malaniuk – Annageldyev, Alushta 2007. } 11. Qb3 Qe7 12. Rb1 Nbd7 13. a4 Rfb8 { The rook is rather useless on this square.   Preferable was:  13...Rfe8  14.b5  axb5   worse is  14...a5  15.Ra1  Rad8  16.Ba3  as trading dark-squared bishops weakens the c7-pawn:  16...h6  17.Bxd6  cxd6   or  17...Qxd6  18.Rac1  +=  18.Rac1  += when White has a pleasant position, as in Ionov – Shaposhnikov, St Petersburg 2003  15.axb5  Ne4 !  When White must probably accept the challenge and sacrifice an exchange with:  16.Nxd5  Bxd5  17.Qxd5  Nc3  18.Qb3  Nxb1  19.Qxb1   or  19.Bxb1  Nf6  20.e4  Nxe4  21.Re1  Qe6  22.Qxe6  Rxe6  23.Bxe4  Ra1  ∞ when Black will regain the two bishops for a rook  19...Nf6  Controlling the e4-square, with an approximately level game. } 14. b5 axb5 15. axb5 g6 { The typical  15...Ne4 ?!  does not work well due to  16.Nxd5  Bxd5  17.Qxd5  Nc3  18.Qc4  Nxb1  19.Bxb1  += with very good compensation for the exchange, as Black cannot prevent the advance e3-e4 with:  19...Nf6 ?!  20.e4 !  Nxe4 ?  21.Re1  +- This variation illustrates why Black’s rook on  e8  was important. } 16. h3 h6 { Again, the desired  16...Ne4  is met by  17.Nxd5  Bxd5  18.Qxd5  Nc3  19.Qc6  Nxb1  20.Bxb1  += followed by e3-e4. } 17. Re1 { Beginning to prepare the break e3-e4. } 17... Ra7 { Once again:  17...Ne4  18.Nxd5 !  += } 18. Bb2 { An interesting alternative was  18.Bxg6 !?  fxg6  19.e4  with a dangerous initiative, for example  19...Nh5  20.e5  Ba3  21.Bxh6  Nf8   21...Qe6 ?  22.Ng5 !  +- followed by  Nxd5  22.g4  Ng7  23.Nxd5  with an attack. } 18... Qe6 { Protecting d5, hoping for the desired 19...Ne4. } 19. Nd2 { Reinforcing the control of e4, White is almost ready to break in the centre. } 19... Rba8 { Note how ineffective Black’s play is on the queenside, as after so many moves there is still no semblance of a threat.   Unfortunately for Black  19...Ne4 ?  simply loses a pawn after  20.Ncxe4  dxe4  21.Qxe6  fxe6  22.Nxe4. } 20. Qc2 Bf8 21. e4 { ± The desired break at the right time. White gains a very powerful initiative in the centre, and Black is unable to deal with it. } 21... dxe4 { It was preferable to simply give up a pawn with  21...Qe7  22.exd5   or  22.e5 !?  ±  22...Qd8  23.Bc4  ± though Black still needs to be careful with tactical shots, such as d5-d6 threatening  Qxg6. } 22. Ndxe4 Bxe4 { 22...Nxe4  is no improvement:  23.d5 !  Qe7   or  23...Bxd5  24.Nxd5  Qxd5  25.Bxe4  Qxb5  when White does not bother with  Bxa8  , but instead  26.Bxg6 !  +-  24.Nxe4  (threatening Nf6)  24...Qd8  25.Qc3  f6  26.Bc2  followed by  Qg3  with a decisive attack. } 23. Nxe4 Bg7 { The alternative  23...Nxe4  is a nice illustration of White’s positional dominance; after  24.Bxe4  Re8  25.Re3 !  White’s advantage does not rely on a specific tactical shot, but rather on his great piece coordination, and Black’s inability to protect the back rank, as illustrated by the variation:  25...Qd6  26.Rbe1  Bg7  27.Qc4  Rf8  28.Bc2  Nf6   28...Raa8  29.Re6 !  +-  29.Bb3  Raa8  30.Re7  +- } 24. Bc4 Qf5 25. g4 { An unlikely yet highly effective resource, taking advantage of the awkward location of Black’s queen.   The more standard  25.Re3 !?  should also be winning. } 25... Qf3 { Instead  25...Qf4 ?  loses to  26.Bc1  Qf3  27.Rb3  and the queen is trapped.   There is nothing to hope for after  25...Nxg4  26.hxg4  Qxg4+  27.Ng3. } 26. Re3 Qf4 27. Ng3 { Threatening Qxg6. } 27... Nf8 28. Bxf7+ { A nice blow! The attack is overwhelming and White finished off the game with ease. } 28... Kh7 { The bishop is immune, because of  28...Kxf7 ?  29.Qb3+  Ne6  30.Rxe6  Kf8  31.Rbe1  followed by  Re7  , and White wins. } 29. Bb3 Rd8 30. Rbe1 Rd7 31. Re5 Ra8 32. Qc4 Rad8 33. R1e4 Qd2 { Not  33...Nxe4 ??  34.Qg8#. } 34. Bc3 Qc1+ 35. Kg2 Nd5 36. Ne2 Qa3 37. Nf4 Bxe5 38. Nxd5 Rxd5 39. Rxe5 c6 { Again, not  39...Rxe5 ??  40.Qg8#. } 40. Bb4 Qa8 41. bxc6 b5 42. Qxd5 Rxd5 43. Bxd5 { Black resigns. The final position is quite picturesque. The strong c6-pawn, together with White’s bishops, makes the position impossible to defend, for example:  43...Qd8  44.c7  Qxc7  45.Re7+  Final remarks  1. Whenever Black arranges his pawns as in the game, with a7-b6-c7, White must carefully analyze whether he will be able to dispute Black’s control of the e4-square. If that is not the case, something is likely to go wrong.  2. If White can dispute the e4-square, then the plan b4-b5 followed by an eventual e3-e4 is very powerful, as it opens many lines for attack. Positionally, it also makes sense, as Black’s backward c7-pawn and the c6-square may become vulnerable after e3-e4, especially if light-squared bishops are traded on e4.   3. Finally, Black had nothing to hope for down the a-file or on the queenside for that matter. Hence Black’s 13th move proved to be an utter waste of time. } *

