{ @@HeaderStart@@Magnus Carlsen – Viswanathan Anand, Tal Memorial, Moscow 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game shows how White can successfully carry out the central break e3-e4. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2 d5 6. a3 Be7 7. cxd5 { 7...exd5  is analyzed in the next game. } 7... Nxd5 8. Bd2 Nd7 9. g3 b6 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bg2 Bb7 { The game Getz – Agdestein clearly illustrated how White’s bishop is often poorly placed on d2 in this structure. Did Carlsen miss this concept? Of course not! } 12. Bb4 { Finding an unusual route to make use of this bishop. } 12... Nf6 { If  12...c5  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Bc3  White has a slightly favourable version of the hanging pawns structure, as he has already traded one minor piece and his bishop on  g2  puts pressure on the d5-pawn.   Dubious is  12...Bxb4+ ?!  13.axb4  Qe7  14.Qb3  Nf6  15.O-O  += followed by  Rfc1  when White can exert pressure down the a- and c-files. } 13. O-O Re8 14. Rc1 c6 15. Bxe7 Rxe7 { The dark-squared bishops are off the board and White has a small advantage since the c6-pawn is already a weakness due to the advance ...b7-b6. } 16. Re1 { The reader should pay close attention to this move, as it is the beginning of a new plan in our toolbox.   The plan  16.b4 ?!  is not as powerful since Black will respond to an eventual b4-b5 with  ...cxb5  as the d5-pawn is well protected. } 16... Qd6 17. Nf4 Bc8 { Transposing into a hanging pawns structure with  17...c5  18.dxc5  bxc5  puts Black under definite pressure after:  19.Qc2  Rc8  20.Red1  += } 18. Qa4 Rc7 19. f3 { Excellent; Carlsen chooses the perfect occasion to execute the typical plan e3-e4. } 19... Be6 { The try  19...c5  is met by  20.e4 !  posing great problems since after  20...dxe4 ?   or  20...Be6  21.dxc5  Rxc5  22.Rcd1  ±  21.fxe4  +- the threat e4-e5 is even stronger, as there is a discovered attack on the a8-rook as well. } 20. e4 dxe4 { Underestimating White’s tactical resources.   A better defence was  20...Qd7  21.Nxe6   or  21.e5  c5  22.Qxd7  Nxd7  23.Ne2  +=  21...Qxe6  22.e5  Ne8  23.Rc3  += when White enjoys a pleasant advantage in a flexible position. } 21. fxe4 { Note how the influence of White’s bishop on g2 has been enhanced by the plan f2-f3 and e3-e4. Black’s position is uncomfortable due to multiple threats, such as e4-e5 winning a piece. } 21... Qd7 { If  21...b5  22.Qb4 !  Qxb4  23.axb4  Black is in severe trouble. For example,  23...Rac8  24.Rc3  Bg4  25.e5  Ne8  26.Rec1  and Black’s position falls apart. } 22. d5 { A nice tactical blow, breaking Black’s defence. } 22... cxd5 23. Qxd7 Rxd7 24. Nxe6 fxe6 25. Bh3 { The key move; Black cannot avoid losing a pawn. } 25... Kh8 { Another option was:  25...Re8  26.exd5  Rdd8 !   inaccurate is  26...Kh8 ?!  27.Rxe6 !  27.Bxe6+  Kh8  28.Red1  ± White has a full extra pawn, but Black survives a little longer.   Worse is  25...Re7 ?!  26.exd5. } 26. e5 Ng8 27. Bxe6 Rdd8 { Making the win easier.   Instead  27...Re7  28.Bxd5  Rd8  allows Black to resist longer:  29.Bb3 !?  ± } 28. Rc7 d4 29. Bd7 { +- Black resigns in view of Rd1 followed by Rxd4.  Final remarks  1. White’s move 12.Bb4 should be remembered. Carlsen understood the dark-squared bishop was useless inside the pawn chain as we learned earlier, so he found an unusual way to trade it.  2. The e3-e4 break is particularly strong with a bishop on g2. Most importantly, this break is even stronger if Black has played ...b7-b6 weakening the c6-pawn.  3. Black’s capture 20...dxe4 is illogical, as it clears the way for the bishop on g2. After this mistake Black’s position became extremely fragile, causing an early collapse. } *

