{ @@HeaderStart@@Yuriy Kuzubov – Zahar Efimenko, Kiev 2012@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. This is an example of how Black may neutralize White’s attempt to break with e3-e4.   2. After the break e3-e4 is carried out under unfavourable circumstances, the game turns into a bad version of a white isolani, which Black wins convincingly. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2 d5 6. a3 Be7 7. cxd5 exd5 8. g3 Nbd7 9. Bg2 Nb6 10. Qc2 a5 { When followed by ...a5-a4 this is generally a good idea to gain some critical squares on the queenside. } 11. O-O Re8 12. Bd2 { An alternative was  12.b3  Bf8  13.Rd1  g6   maybe better is  13...Bg4  14.f3  Bd7  followed by  ...c7-c5  with counterplay  14.f3  Bg7  15.e4  dxe4  16.fxe4  c6  17.a4  += when White achieves comfortable control of the centre, as in the game M. Gurevich – Polaczek, Philadelphia 1989. } 12... a4 13. Rae1 Bd7 { Placing the bishop on d7 is only a temporary necessity, and it can be followed by ...Qc8 and ...Bf5  (or ...Bh3)  improving Black’s control of the light squares. } 14. Nf4 { The alternative  14.f3  is well met by  14...c5 !  15.dxc5  Bxc5  =+ when Black obtains a favourable version of the isolani due to White’s weakened central structure and the useful a4-pawn, which secures a strong outpost on  c4  for one of Black’s knights. } 14... c6 15. e4 { Transposing into an isolated queen pawn structure.   Unfortunately White’s position is not ideally suited for the more typical plan  15.f3  intending to follow with e3-e4, because of  15...Nc4  16.Bc1   but not  16.Nxa4 ?  Nxd2  -+  16...b5  when Black manages to create some pressure on the centre and kingside, preventing White’s active plans. For example:  17.Kh1   or  17.e4 ?!  dxe4  18.fxe4  Qb6  19.Rd1  Bg4  =+ when White’s centre is more of a weakness than a strength  17...Qb6  18.Rd1  b4 !  ∞ With good active play for Black. } 15... dxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 g6 { We have reached a critical position. There is already one minor piece off the board and White does not have clear attacking chances, therefore I find his position rather delicate, meaning that a few inaccuracies will lead to a much inferior endgame. } 18. h4 { An alternative was  18.d5  eliminating the isolated pawn:  18...cxd5  19.Nxd5  Nxd5  20.Bxd5  However, Black can find complications with  20...Bb5 !?   or  20...Bf6 =  since White’s rook is trapped on f1:  21.Qe4 !  Ra6   or  21...Bxf1  22.Qf3  Rf8  23.Kxf1 =  followed by  Bh6  regaining the exchange  22.Bc3  Bxf1  23.Kxf1  Rf8  ∞ White seems to have sufficient compensation for the exchange. } 18... Bd6 19. Kh2 { An inconsequential move.   Logical was  19.h5  Qf6  20.Qd3  with level chances. } 19... Qf6 20. Qd3 { Unfortunately  20.d5 ?  is no longer possible due to:  20...Nxd5  21.Bxd5  cxd5  22.Nxd5 ?  Qxh4  +-+ } 20... Bg4 { White’s position becomes unpleasant. } 21. Bg2 Bc7 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Rc1 Qf5 { Trading queens only emphasizes the weakness of the d4-pawn. } 24. Qxf5 Bxf5 25. Bf3 { 25.d5 !?  was probably better:  25...Rd8 !   incorrect is  25...Bxf4 ?!  26.Bxf4  Nxd5  27.Bxd5  cxd5  28.Rc7  when Black cannot maintain his advantage after  28...d4  29.Rxb7  Re2  30.Bh6  !!1  26.Bf3   but not  26.dxc6 ?  Rxd2  27.cxb7  Rc2 !  ∓  26...Bxf4  27.Bxf4  Nxd5  28.Be5  Be6  =+ White does not have enough counterplay for the pawn, but at least stays in the game with reasonable fighting chances. } 25... h5 26. Be3 Be4 { It is a good decision to trade White’s light-squared bishop in order to gain control of the precious d5-square. } 27. Kg2 Bxf4 28. Bxf4 Bxf3+ 29. Kxf3 Nd5 { It may be too soon for my assertion that Black has a clear advantage, but after analyzing the rest of the game the reader might start to agree with me. From a strategic point of view, matters are quite clear, as White has reached an endgame where the isolated d4-pawn is nothing but weak and blockaded. White’s bishop on f4 has no targets whatsoever and sees its action restricted by its own pawns. All Black needs is patience and some creativity to find the right plan, which Efimenko does quite well. } 30. Bd2 f6 31. Rc4 Ra8 { Of course not  31...Nb6 ?  32.Rb4  ± winning a pawn. } 32. Ke4 Kf7 33. Kd3 Ke6 34. f3 Ra6 { This allows White an extra option. } 35. Bc1 { Returning the favour.   White had an opportunity to reduce his problems with  35.g4 !?  Kd7  =+ when things are less clear, but Black still preserves a small edge   instead  35...Rb6  is well met by  36.Kc2  Rb3  37.gxh5  gxh5  38.Rxa4  Rxf3  39.Ra7  b5  40.Rh7  when White has decent counterplay } 35... Kf5 { Preventing g3-g4 as well as preparing the key ...g6-g5-g4 advance. } 36. Ke2 g5 { Choosing the right plan. By playing ...g5-g4 Black will manage to create a serious weakness on g3. } 37. Kf2 { Somewhat better was:  37.hxg5  fxg5  38.Kf2  g4  The only path to an advantage.  39.Kg2   but not  39.fxg4+ ?  hxg4  ∓ as Black will follow with  ...Ke4  gaining territory and creating the serious threat of  ...Kd3  39...Rb6   or  39...gxf3+  40.Kxf3  Rb6  transposing to  39...Rb6  40.Rxa4  Rb3  41.fxg4+  Kxg4  42.Ra8  Rxg3+  43.Kh2   or  43.Kf2  h4  ∓  43...Nf6  ∓ White’s position is still very difficult due to the passed h-pawn and the poor placement of his king. } 37... g4 38. fxg4+ { This makes Black’s winning task much easier.   An alternative was  38.Kg2  gxf3+  39.Kxf3  Rb6  40.Rxa4  Rb3+  41.Kf2  Kg4  42.Ra8  Rf3+  43.Ke2  Rxg3  ∓ when pushing the f-pawn should be enough to decide the game.   More stubborn was  38.Bd2  Rb6  39.Bb4 !  (blocking the b-file to prevent the deadly penetration with ...Rb3)  39...Ke6  40.fxg4  hxg4  41.Ke2  f5  ∓ though Black has many plans to improve his position, such as  ...Nf6-e4  or  ...Kf7-g6-h5  followed by  ...f5-f4. } 38... Kxg4 39. Rc2 { As often happens, passive defence is ineffective.   39.Kg2  is no better:  39...Rb6  40.Rxa4  Rb3  41.Ra8  Rxg3+  42.Kf2  Kxh4  -+ } 39... Rb6 40. Re2 Rb3 { The g3-pawn is lost, and the rest is simple. } 41. Re4+ Kh3 42. g4 hxg4 43. h5 f5 44. Re1 Kh2 45. h6 Rf3+ 46. Ke2 Rh3 47. Kf1 f4 48. Re2+ Kg3 49. Rg2+ Kf3 { Final remarks  1. Black’s queenside expansion with ...a7-a5-a4, gaining control of the light squares, played an essential role throughout the game and deserves imitation.  2. The reader might think Kuzubov did not know what he was doing, as he left his dark-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. This is not the case: the dark-squared bishop can be inside the pawn chain as long as White is planning the break e3-e4 which would render this bishop useful again.  3. White’s opening did not achieve more than equality. White lost the game because after e3-e4 was played, his inaccuracies forced him into an inferior endgame. A crucial mistake was the slow 19.Kh2 steering White into passive defence. } *

